if you think that a great many

00:01:19.869 --> 00:01:25.759
people who are in responsible
positions at Goldman Sachs and

00:01:25.759 --> 00:01:31.549
similar banks make more money
than they really should.

00:01:31.549 --> 00:01:34.370
Paolo Zanonni:
 Don't be shy.

00:01:34.370 --> 00:01:39.519
Prof: And those who
don't think so?

00:01:39.519 --> 00:01:47.300
I read that as 65/35 in the
affirmative.

00:01:47.300 --> 00:01:53.982
At any rate the--what we're
going to do today is begin with

00:01:53.982 --> 00:02:01.125
an informal discussion looking
at some of Paolo's work over the

00:02:01.125 --> 00:02:05.701
years at Goldman,
whereas, last time we focused

00:02:05.701 --> 00:02:09.000
within the firm,
today we're going to focus on

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:12.008
the firm as an actor in the
larger world,

00:02:12.008 --> 00:02:19.210
and Paolo is going to be--going
to respond to a few questions

00:02:19.210 --> 00:02:25.568
about other endeavors and then
he is going to take the

00:02:25.568 --> 00:02:32.770
microphone and lecture on the
case of the huge Spanish energy

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:38.050
company and battle for control
of it,

00:02:38.050 --> 00:02:43.599
and you'll see when he does
that that the activities of an

00:02:43.599 --> 00:02:48.760
investment banker are pretty
challenging and extremely

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:49.930
complex.
 

00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:57.366
But we'll continue with--well
let's start with--do any of you

00:02:57.366 --> 00:03:02.819
own any garments from Dolce
&amp; Gabbana?

00:03:02.819 --> 00:03:07.930
Does anybody know what it is?
 

00:03:07.930 --> 00:03:18.120
What, pray tell?
 

00:03:18.120 --> 00:03:19.889
Student:  They're a
designer.

00:03:19.889 --> 00:03:21.270
Prof: Okay,
they're a designer.

00:03:21.270 --> 00:03:25.008
Do they just draw things or do
they--they sell things.

00:03:25.008 --> 00:03:25.900
Student:  Make and sell
as well.

00:03:25.900 --> 00:03:27.120
Prof: Okay.
 

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:30.009
Are they for the value
conscious shopper?

00:03:30.009 --> 00:03:30.720
Student:  No.
 

00:03:30.720 --> 00:03:37.303
Prof: No,
they are the inverse of

00:03:37.303 --> 00:03:39.160
Wal-Mart.
 

00:03:39.160 --> 00:03:42.560
Who's higher on the price
schedule than them Paolo,

00:03:42.560 --> 00:03:43.240
anybody?
 

00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:44.116
Paolo Zanonni:
 Hermes,

00:03:44.116 --> 00:03:44.479
I believe.
 

00:03:44.479 --> 00:03:47.690
Prof: Hermes may be
higher, but it's a luxury goods

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:50.639
company,
and Paolo who dresses well,

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:56.006
but so far as I can tell,
doesn't care a bit about luxury

00:03:56.006 --> 00:04:00.688
goods,
is its chairman.

00:04:00.688 --> 00:04:03.128
Tell us about,
just in a few minutes,

00:04:03.128 --> 00:04:07.799
about what the object of your
role there is and how it relates

00:04:07.799 --> 00:04:12.008
to the CEO and the strategic
challenges that come in.

00:04:12.008 --> 00:04:15.826
Paolo Zanonni:
 My role is--the company

00:04:15.826 --> 00:04:20.492
Dolce &amp; Gabbana is about
twenty-three or twenty-four

00:04:20.492 --> 00:04:21.680
years old.
 

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:26.589
It was started by the two
designers and by the CEO.

00:04:26.589 --> 00:04:35.259
It has grown at a rate of about
20% to 25% per year.

00:04:35.259 --> 00:04:42.339
Right before the credit crunch
was--

00:04:42.339 --> 00:04:45.839
when the multiples were about,
let's say,

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:52.543
thirteen to fourteen times
EBITDA, the company was more or

00:04:52.543 --> 00:04:57.129
less worth about $6 billion
dollars,

00:04:57.129 --> 00:05:02.495
but the culture of the company
has remained like the small

00:05:02.495 --> 00:05:06.259
company the two designers
started it,

00:05:06.259 --> 00:05:12.422
and so the reason why--we
developed a friendship out of

00:05:12.422 --> 00:05:13.449
chance.
 

00:05:13.449 --> 00:05:16.709
They have an excellent CEO.
 

00:05:16.709 --> 00:05:21.009
I believe it's probably--in a
country where ladies CEOs are

00:05:21.009 --> 00:05:24.197
rather unusual,
but I think she might be the

00:05:24.197 --> 00:05:27.089
only one of a company of that
size.

00:05:27.089 --> 00:05:31.012
She's really formidable,
one of the best CEOs I have

00:05:31.012 --> 00:05:35.242
met, and so we developed a
friendship with her first and

00:05:35.242 --> 00:05:38.089
with the two designers
afterward.

00:05:38.089 --> 00:05:41.930
At one point they thought that
the main challenge of the

00:05:41.930 --> 00:05:45.980
company was to become more
institutionalized because if you

00:05:45.980 --> 00:05:48.108
look--
especially if you look at

00:05:48.108 --> 00:05:50.855
luxury good companies,
few of them are

00:05:50.855 --> 00:05:52.600
institutionalized.
 

00:05:52.600 --> 00:05:58.516
Because for instance just to
take a few, Armani is not,

00:05:58.516 --> 00:06:03.230
Prada is not,
Dolce &amp; Gabbana is not.

00:06:03.230 --> 00:06:06.069
Gucci is institutionalized.
 

00:06:06.069 --> 00:06:08.980
Prof: Help us--make sure
we understand what's meant by

00:06:08.980 --> 00:06:09.949
institutionalized.
 

00:06:09.949 --> 00:06:14.088
Paolo Zanonni:
 Institutionalized I mean

00:06:14.088 --> 00:06:18.708
companies where,
let's say, the corporate

00:06:18.708 --> 00:06:26.555
functions are very small,
and company's where you have

00:06:26.555 --> 00:06:32.923
culture and processes,
and personalities,

00:06:32.923 --> 00:06:39.579
and recruitment policies,
and leadership selection

00:06:39.579 --> 00:06:47.425
policies that are likely to make
the company successful over the

00:06:47.425 --> 00:06:51.274
long period,
regardless of the influence and

00:06:51.274 --> 00:06:53.009
the survival of the founder.
 

00:06:53.009 --> 00:06:54.829
Prof: So the firm,
its strategies,

00:06:54.829 --> 00:06:59.211
and the job structure,
the structure of employment

00:06:59.211 --> 00:07:03.951
responsibilities becomes
permanent enough to transcend

00:07:03.951 --> 00:07:06.009
the founding group?
 

00:07:06.009 --> 00:07:07.745
Paolo Zanonni:
 Yes and usually the best

00:07:07.745 --> 00:07:09.745
way--
the best way,

00:07:09.745 --> 00:07:14.689
one of the effective ways to do
it,

00:07:14.689 --> 00:07:18.279
so we'll go back to Monday,
one of the effective ways to do

00:07:18.279 --> 00:07:21.500
it is to turn it into a public
liability company,

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:25.589
and have showed us,
and have the discipline,

00:07:25.589 --> 00:07:29.860
and the function of the public
market imposes on you.

00:07:29.860 --> 00:07:33.841
Thus, the entrepreneurs
sometimes don't like to do it

00:07:33.841 --> 00:07:38.088
and so it's--
to try to institutionalize the

00:07:38.088 --> 00:07:42.526
company in that way,
without turning to the public

00:07:42.526 --> 00:07:44.928
market,
which is something that the two

00:07:44.928 --> 00:07:50.610
owners--
they own 90% of the company.

00:07:50.610 --> 00:07:55.690
The remaining 10% is owned by a
few of the senior management.

00:07:55.690 --> 00:07:59.269
The company is a strange
company.

00:07:59.269 --> 00:08:02.838
Since they don't want to access
the public market,

00:08:02.838 --> 00:08:06.569
institutionalize a company with
so--

00:08:06.569 --> 00:08:10.829
such strong personalities
involved not only in designing

00:08:10.829 --> 00:08:16.019
of the goods but in the everyday
life of the company is not easy.

00:08:16.019 --> 00:08:19.430
They say that I could--that I
could be helpful.

00:08:19.430 --> 00:08:24.339
So far we haven't done very
much, but--anyways it's a lot of

00:08:24.339 --> 00:08:24.839
fun.
 

00:08:24.839 --> 00:08:26.769
I have to tell you it's a lot
of fun.

00:08:26.769 --> 00:08:32.051
Prof: Another industrial
sector that you have very

00:08:32.051 --> 00:08:36.389
substantial experience with is
cars, with Ford,

00:08:36.389 --> 00:08:39.690
Fiat, Volvo and General Motors.
 

00:08:39.690 --> 00:08:40.860
Have I got that right?
 

00:08:40.860 --> 00:08:41.120
Paolo Zanonni:  Yeah.
 

00:08:41.120 --> 00:08:42.259
Prof: Did I miss
something?

00:08:42.259 --> 00:08:44.389
Paolo Zanonni:  No.
 

00:08:44.389 --> 00:08:48.049
I have less--unless you want to
talk about trucks.

00:08:48.049 --> 00:08:50.381
Prof: Well--
Paolo Zanonni:

00:08:50.381 --> 00:08:52.389
 The two sectors are
different,

00:08:52.389 --> 00:08:57.269
but you have trucks in--for
people who used to have trucks,

00:08:57.269 --> 00:08:59.639
there's a fair number of truck
companies.

00:08:59.639 --> 00:09:04.384
Prof: I actually thought
your experience with helping to

00:09:04.384 --> 00:09:07.600
bring General Motors and Fiat
together,

00:09:07.600 --> 00:09:12.807
and then helping them to
separate themselves was very

00:09:12.807 --> 00:09:17.222
interesting,
and your views about the sort

00:09:17.222 --> 00:09:21.553
of informal compact that seemed,
at that time,

00:09:21.553 --> 00:09:24.370
to regulate the Detroit car
companies,

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:30.062
and which probably wasn't a
great influence on the

00:09:30.062 --> 00:09:35.784
survivability of General Motors,
seemed like a very interesting

00:09:35.784 --> 00:09:38.820
topic if you could give us some
a few minutes on that.

00:09:38.820 --> 00:09:42.269
Paolo Zanonni:  Okay.
 

00:09:42.269 --> 00:09:50.320
One of the peculiarities of the
car industry worldwide,

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:54.240
definitely the car industry in
Europe,

00:09:54.240 --> 00:10:02.126
is that it's one of the few
industries that has been plagued

00:10:02.126 --> 00:10:09.480
by over capacity for at least
the last thirty years,

00:10:09.480 --> 00:10:15.511
and one of the few industries
in which this over capacity have

00:10:15.511 --> 00:10:19.269
never been taken out of the
system,

00:10:19.269 --> 00:10:24.635
but in which the players
have--at least until last year

00:10:24.635 --> 00:10:27.320
it was easier to survive.
 

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:29.899
This is a very peculiar
situation,

00:10:29.899 --> 00:10:35.691
because if you look at most
private industries in which

00:10:35.691 --> 00:10:40.840
there is a large degree of
private ownership,

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:44.940
and more or less,
the rules of capitalism apply,

00:10:44.940 --> 00:10:50.365
at least to a large extent,
you really seldom have such a

00:10:50.365 --> 00:10:56.860
high degree of over capacity and
the survival of all the players.

00:10:56.860 --> 00:11:01.230
Not only--but I'm not up to
date so--

00:11:01.230 --> 00:11:04.719
but let's say that up to five
years ago or six years ago when

00:11:04.719 --> 00:11:09.178
I used to be up to date,
capacity had been not taken off

00:11:09.178 --> 00:11:11.230
the system but added.
 

00:11:11.230 --> 00:11:15.841
There is--we will have to
search long and hard to find

00:11:15.841 --> 00:11:20.158
situations,
in which productive facilities

00:11:20.158 --> 00:11:24.488
have been shut down,
and on the contrary,

00:11:24.488 --> 00:11:30.662
we find a lot of instances in
which new productive facilities

00:11:30.662 --> 00:11:35.288
have been built,
but none has been shut down.

00:11:35.288 --> 00:11:37.899
Actually you could argue with
that number;

00:11:37.899 --> 00:11:44.898
that you could argue that
actually the over capacity has

00:11:44.898 --> 00:11:46.678
grown worse.
 

00:11:46.678 --> 00:11:50.405
Players--the players have
been--I mean they are not stupid

00:11:50.405 --> 00:11:52.672
people,
they are conscious of the fact

00:11:52.672 --> 00:11:55.360
that they're operating in the
industry which is,

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:59.636
or which was,
but I think still is plagued by

00:11:59.636 --> 00:12:04.418
over capacity,
and so except for drastic

00:12:04.418 --> 00:12:11.048
reduction in capacity start
closing down factories,

00:12:11.048 --> 00:12:14.961
they have been trying to
address this situation in every

00:12:14.961 --> 00:12:16.028
possible way.
 

00:12:16.028 --> 00:12:21.754
One the ways--one of the most
traditional ways that have been

00:12:21.754 --> 00:12:27.576
used has been different types of
joint ventures and/or mergers

00:12:27.576 --> 00:12:29.580
and acquisitions.
 

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:36.926
One of the actions that was
supposed to change the face of

00:12:36.926 --> 00:12:45.044
the industry was the acquisition
of Chrysler by Daimler-Benz but

00:12:45.044 --> 00:12:52.158
I think that they--
the absorption didn't work well.

00:12:52.158 --> 00:12:55.307
Daimler lost a lot of money,
and afterward,

00:12:55.307 --> 00:12:58.678
Chrysler was sold to a private
equity firm.

00:12:58.678 --> 00:13:03.695
The only case that I know of,
of a reasonably large car

00:13:03.695 --> 00:13:07.596
company being shut down,
is the old British

00:13:07.596 --> 00:13:10.288
&gt;
 

00:13:10.288 --> 00:13:13.721
that was sold to a private
equity firm and

00:13:13.721 --> 00:13:16.149
Dr&gt;
 

00:13:16.149 --> 00:13:22.428
The brand was sold to a Chinese
producer that wanted to have a

00:13:22.428 --> 00:13:24.178
European brand.
 

00:13:24.178 --> 00:13:29.014
Prof: Without getting
down to details--well broad

00:13:29.014 --> 00:13:33.500
details but the compact that
seemed to operate--

00:13:33.500 --> 00:13:37.125
Prof: --between
management and labor have

00:13:37.125 --> 00:13:38.361
adequate--
Paolo Zanonni:

00:13:38.361 --> 00:13:38.649
 And government.
 

00:13:38.649 --> 00:13:40.788
Prof: About the
management of another.

00:13:40.788 --> 00:13:41.860
Paolo Zanonni:
 The government.

00:13:41.860 --> 00:13:44.614
Prof: And the
government--spell that out a

00:13:44.614 --> 00:13:45.360
little bit.
 

00:13:45.360 --> 00:13:48.825
Paolo Zanonni:
 It was--it's different in

00:13:48.825 --> 00:13:50.298
different nations.
 

00:13:50.298 --> 00:13:56.427
Let's say that--let's be
general, which is my impression

00:13:56.427 --> 00:14:03.000
in working for them was that
there were little incentives in

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:08.682
vigorously addressing the
situation with the kind of

00:14:08.682 --> 00:14:13.139
action that you would be
needing,

00:14:13.139 --> 00:14:17.340
and that was because,
let's take for instance,

00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:24.370
let's take an adversary view of
a relationship in the workplace,

00:14:24.370 --> 00:14:28.921
let's suppose the management
would have liked to close down

00:14:28.921 --> 00:14:30.019
one factory.
 

00:14:30.019 --> 00:14:35.990
The degree of unionization,
the degree of--

00:14:35.990 --> 00:14:39.323
in the whole company,
the degree of a relationship in

00:14:39.323 --> 00:14:43.107
countries different from the
United States between the union

00:14:43.107 --> 00:14:47.403
and political parties,
the degree of influence of the

00:14:47.403 --> 00:14:52.249
union's own government,
and in addition the degree to

00:14:52.249 --> 00:14:56.921
which the life of the company
itself depends on the

00:14:56.921 --> 00:14:58.230
government.
 

00:14:58.230 --> 00:15:04.003
You have seen an example in the
last credit crunch in which the

00:15:04.003 --> 00:15:09.870
purchase of new cars is in fact
subsidized by the government.

00:15:09.870 --> 00:15:13.230
This is new in the states,
but it's not new in Europe,

00:15:13.230 --> 00:15:15.945
it's--as far as I'm concerned
this is the third one that I've

00:15:15.945 --> 00:15:18.350
seen in Europe,
it's not the first one.

00:15:18.350 --> 00:15:25.600
You have this very strange
situation in which management,

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:28.850
the union, and the government
become,

00:15:28.850 --> 00:15:33.134
to some extent,
dependent on each other and the

00:15:33.134 --> 00:15:37.700
last thing they want is to upset
this balance,

00:15:37.700 --> 00:15:41.702
and the result,
no extra capacity is taken off

00:15:41.702 --> 00:15:42.860
the system.
 

00:15:42.860 --> 00:15:47.240
No serious restructuring is
being done.

00:15:47.240 --> 00:15:49.365
Prof: So the--
Paolo Zanonni:

00:15:49.365 --> 00:15:50.519
 Now it is,
now it is;

00:15:50.519 --> 00:15:53.039
now probably it is with the use
of Chapter 11.

00:15:53.039 --> 00:15:54.038
Prof: Yes.
 

00:15:54.038 --> 00:15:57.009
Paolo Zanonni:
 It's a huge--with a huge

00:15:57.009 --> 00:16:00.368
financial crisis and the use of
Chapter 11, which has

00:16:00.368 --> 00:16:03.210
allowed--I'll tell you a
personal story.

00:16:03.210 --> 00:16:05.971
I worked for Fiat,
as a manager,

00:16:05.971 --> 00:16:11.135
for about fifteen years and I
worked with Goldman for about

00:16:11.135 --> 00:16:12.740
fifteen years.
 

00:16:12.740 --> 00:16:16.178
In sum--fourteen and fifteen
years in sum--

00:16:16.178 --> 00:16:20.316
if there is one deal that I
tried to do three times has been

00:16:20.316 --> 00:16:26.210
Fiat's acquisition of Chrysler,
and I failed three times.

00:16:26.210 --> 00:16:27.360
Prof: Aren't you lucky?
 

00:16:27.360 --> 00:16:27.830
Paolo Zanonni:  No.
 

00:16:27.830 --> 00:16:31.596
I think it was one of the deals
that make more sense in the

00:16:31.596 --> 00:16:35.171
industry, and this time,
Fiat management was successful,

00:16:35.171 --> 00:16:37.120
but why it was successful?
 

00:16:37.120 --> 00:16:42.106
It was successful because
Chrysler was not sold by the

00:16:42.106 --> 00:16:45.467
owner;
it was practically given to

00:16:45.467 --> 00:16:51.168
them by the Federal government
in exchange for an industrial

00:16:51.168 --> 00:16:54.840
product, and practically debt
free.

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:57.984
As you can see,
the industry is changing,

00:16:57.984 --> 00:17:02.778
but again it's changing because
one--because of Chapter 11 and

00:17:02.778 --> 00:17:06.630
because of the size of this
financial crisis.

00:17:06.630 --> 00:17:10.057
The compact between the three
players has broken down,

00:17:10.057 --> 00:17:11.480
totally broken down.
 

00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:13.148
Prof: Well and--
Paolo Zanonni:

00:17:13.148 --> 00:17:14.170
 Same thing with General
Motors.

00:17:14.170 --> 00:17:18.404
Prof: The car industry
preserving these legacy firms

00:17:18.404 --> 00:17:22.275
runs against the tide of
creative destruction that you

00:17:22.275 --> 00:17:25.049
expect in capitalist
industries--

00:17:25.049 --> 00:17:26.318
Paolo Zanonni:  Totally.
 

00:17:26.318 --> 00:17:30.747
Prof: --and that's
highlighted by the fact that you

